These thoughts probably require more specification than a twitter thread can provide, but this is the general gist of what I've been chewing on lately.

into questions of the general organization of society. In this sense, I think the political subject which stops climate change is - and can only be - the revolutionary proletariat which is the only class capable of taking this infinite potential.

It also means communist thought needs to focus very strongly on the infinite potential of labour. We must accept that all labour effort transforms nature and raise consciousness about what that transformation really means. Which extends beyond just the climate question but also

climate change has reached a point that it will be seriously damaging human lives, at which point it will be much harder to solve. It also means reformist policies are useless, since we need to transform the basic condition of labour or it will remain locked in.

The implication of this is simple; nothing short of the socialist transformation of society will solve the climate crisis. This isn't a new thesis but I don't think people grasp the implications of it. It means we need to take far more drastic and risky action or wait until

I do think the term "alienation" *can* be used to refer to the entrapment of labour's potential under capitalism. Which pushes human activity towards damaging the climate by various mechanisms, but this problem has to be overcome *before* we tackle climate change.

an industrial/urban society.  This sort of naturalism is also not directly connected to climate change. After all, humans were building parks and gardens in ancient times. In the present it's political appeal is vague and not innately transformative (see ecofash and primitivists)

I think some theorize an alienation from nature, but this doesn't hold up well as a thesis. "Nature" - as these debates have shown - is a pretty vague thing. The closest you get is a general affinity for like, trees and grass and open spaces, but these can be achieved within

in the latter. Yes, capitalist organization in it's current form is the primary root cause of climate change but this isn't clear in the immediate relationship of social organization. The only potential for it to become clear is in the *aftermath*.

Unlike other events Climate Change doesn't present itself in a very clear way. The dialectic of exploited/exploiter is a very definitive situation. It's present in both the broad strokes of social life and the immediate lived social reality, whereas climate change is only present
